fr.sorbonne_u.devs_simulation.models

Class CoupledModel

  • java.lang.Object
    • fr.sorbonne_u.devs_simulation.models.Model
      • fr.sorbonne_u.devs_simulation.models.CoupledModel
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    ModelDescriptionI, ParentNotificationI, CoupledModelI, ModelI, java.io.Serializable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    MoleneModel, PortableComputerModel, WiFiModel

    public abstract class CoupledModel
extends Model
implements CoupledModelI
    The class CoupledModel implements the most general methods and instance variables for DEVS coupled models.

    Description

    The class implement a polymorphic coordination algorithm able to take into account the three kinds of atomic simulation models implemented in the library i.e., standard DEVS atomic models, event scheduling view (ES) atomic models and hybrid system models inspired from Lynch et al. hybrid input/output automata (HIOA) and timed input/output automata (TIOA). Hence, it is meant to be used as the base class of any user defined coupled model. However, the library may include in the future other implementations of coupled models including the coordination of other types of simulation models of providing specialised and more efficient coordination algorithms for specific subsets of types of simulation models or even coordination algorithm tailored to homogeneous sets of submodels of the same type.

    As coordination is concerned, event scheduling view atomic models needs nothing more than what is already required to coordinate standard DEVS atomic models. Both exchanges external events exported by some models and imported by others. When creating a coupled model, it is therefore required to define the connections among the submodels. it is also required to define the events that are imported by the coupled model, the submodels that consume them and, when necessary, how to convert a coupled model imported event into the type of events imported by each consuming submodel. Finally, it is also required to define the events that are exported by the submodels and reexported by the coupled model. Because the type of event exported by the coupled model nned not be the same as the one exported by the submodel, a conversion function can also be defined.

    HIOA atomic models add a very different aspect to the standard DEVS atomic models as they are defined over continuous and discrete variables that may be exported and imported among them. In a manner similar to the events, a coupled model must define its imported variables and the submodels that consume them, its exported variables and the submodels that export them and the internal bindings of variables exported by a submodel and imported by other submodels.

    Besides the management of variables, HIOA models introduce a much tighter coupling between models that share variables. At initialisation time, the order through which variables are evaluated needs to follow their export/import dependencies, exported variables being initialised before their bound imported ones can be used to further initialise other internal or exported variables which need them to be computed. Hence, a coupled model that coordinates HIOA and other types of models must be able to partition them into unsorted models exhibiting no dependencies (but the production/consumption of events) and sorted ones which are sharing variables.

    In many DEVS coordination algorithms, the protocol assumes that when a submodel is active at some simulation step i.e., performs its next internal transition, other models can only execute external events produced by the internal transition of the active submodel. But this may be restrictive for many kinds of HIOA. HIOA do not impose a way to represent the continuous trajectories. One may use differential equations, but equally well algebraic equations. Most models based on differential equations consider that a variable can be updated by evaluating its equations using the last computed values of the variables upon which they depend. As the integration step is usually small, so is the error made by doing so (some integration algorithms use simple extrapolations without reevaluating these variables per se). When algebraic models are used, it can be important to reevaluate all of the variables before performing the internal step initially decided by the coordination algorithm. Hence, this implementation of DEVS considers that whenever a sorted submodel is selected to perform the next internal transition, all of the sorted submodels is given the possibility to perform an internal transition in their order of dependency.

    To support the management of sorted/unsorted models, each type of models define a method isOrdered, and when they are ordered, they are placed into the subset of sorted models over which a topological sort is done. Currently, the topological sort is done over the variable production/consumption relationship (partial order). If other types of ordered models must be added, the notion of order will have to be extended to take them into account.

      • internalTransition

        public void internalTransition()
        Description copied from interface: ModelI
        perform the next internal transition, both calling the method userDefinedInternalTransition and doing all of the necessary internal catering work.

        Description

        In the standard DEVS protocol, this method is assumed to be defined by users in their atomic models. However, having only one method to do so makes it difficult to include common behaviours for models. Moreover, DEVS allows to define new types of models where specific common behaviours must be implemented. With the traditional DEVS vision, this would end up asking the users to cater for these common behaviours in each of their implementations the method, an error-prone burden put on their shoulders. In this library, we prefer to split transitions in two parts:

        • a library defined part, here internalTransition, which implementations in abstract classes include their common behaviours and, for atomic models, calls the user model specific part;
        • a user model-specific part, here userDefinedInternalTransition, which implements the execution internal events of the user-defined models per se.

        After the execution of the method, the relationships between timeAdvance, getTimeOfNextEvent, getNextTimeAdvance and getCurrentStateTime() is restored to reflect the wait for the next internal event.

        Contract

         pre     getTimeOfNextEvent().lessThan(Time.INFINITY)
 pre     getNextTimeAdvance().equals(getTimeOfNextEvent().subtract(getCurrentStateTime()))
 post    getTimeOfNextEvent().equals(Time.INFINITY) || getTimeOfNextEvent().subtract(getCurrentStateTime()).equals(getNextTimeAdvance())
        Specified by:
        internalTransition in interface ModelI
        See Also:
        ModelI.internalTransition()

      • causalTransition

        public void causalTransition(Time current)
        Description copied from interface: ModelI
        perform a causal transition i.e., an internal transition triggered by the internal transition of an influenced model; causal transitions do not produce external events.

        Description

        This method has been introduced by the library when the HIOA models defined by algebraic equations were introduced in order to allow an implementation that reevaluates variables on request only. For other models, new variable values and events are produced by the execution of events, but in this case, this allows an influenced model to require new values only when they are needed this reducing the computational workload.

        Therefore, the causal transition should be used to implement a lazy evaluation of the variables upon which another variable depends in another model. In this case, the internal transition of the depending model will trigger causal transitions on each of the models that provide values for variables upon which the former depends. This is indeed recursive. For example, imagine a model A that depends upon variables provided by models B and C, with C also depending on variables provided by a model D. Then, one can program the model A such that it has planned internal transitions to update its variables, but all of the others would have no planned internal transitions but only causal transitions triggered by the internal transition of A. In this case, the models will be sorted in dependency order D, C, B, A and then each of them will be activated for causal transition (D, C, B) and for internal transition (A). For HIOA models, this can force a unique integration step for all variables or perform a lazy update for variables that are computed using an algebraic equation.

        Of course, one can also decide to have internal transitions only and therefore decide locally to each HIOA model when to update their variables. In this case, depending models use the latest value of all of the variables they depend upon, which can cause larger numerical errors. When a unique integration step must be chosen among several variables so to minimise the numerical errors for all of the variables, the inherent coupling that this supposes should push the programmer to create a single model to integrate all of these variables together. Otherwise, their would be a need for a dynamic negotiation of the integration steps hard to put in place within the DEVS protocol.

        Contract

         pre     isInitialised()
 pre     current != null
 pre     current.greaterThanOrEqual(getCurrentStateTime())
 pre     current.lessThanOrEqual(this.getTimeOfNextEvent())
 pre     getCurrentStateTime().lessThanOrEqual(getTimeOfNextEvent())
 post    getTimeOfNextEvent().equals(Time.INFINITY) || getTimeOfNextEvent().subtract(getCurrentStateTime()).equals(getNextTimeAdvance())

      • externalTransition

        public void externalTransition(Duration elapsedTime)
        Description copied from interface: ModelI
        do the next external transition, both calling the method userDefinedExternalTransition and doing all of the necessary internal catering work.

        Description

        In the standard DEVS protocol, this method is assumed to be defined by users in their atomic models. However, having only one method to do so makes it difficult to include common behaviours for models. Moreover, DEVS allows to define new types of models where specific common behaviours must be implemented. With the traditional DEVS vision, this would end up asking the users to cater for these common behaviours in each of their implementations the method, an error-prone burden put on their shoulders. In this library, we prefer to split transitions in two parts:

        • a library defined part, here externalTransition, which implementations in abstract classes include their common behaviours and, for atomic models, calls the user model specific part;
        • a user model-specific part, here userDefinedExternalTransition, which implements the execution internal events of the user-defined models per se.

        After the execution of the method, the relationships between timeAdvance, getTimeOfNextEvent(), getNextTimeAdvance and getCurrentStateTime() is restored to reflect the wait for the next internal event.

 post    getTimeOfNextEvent().equals(Time.INFINITY) || getTimeOfNextEvent().subtract(getCurrentStateTime()).equals(getNextTimeAdvance())
